> We're sautéing beef with onions and oregano to give these quesadillas extra flavor. Instead of cooking them one-by-one in a pan, we've come up with a technique to get crispy, gooey quesadillas in the oven. Black bean-avocado salsa is a hearty and delicious twist on traditional salsa.

== Salsa ==

Halve, pit, and dice the @avocado{2}. In a #medium bowl{}, combine the avocado, @black beans{1%box}(drained and rinsed), @grape tomatoes{8%oz}(halved), @cilantro{1/2%oz}(finely chopped), and a squeeze of @lime{1}. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

== Quesadillas ==

Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%box}. Halve, peel, and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Finely chop the @cilantro{1/2%oz}(finely chopped). Halve the @grape tomatoes{8%oz}(halved).

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add the onion to the pan and cook, tossing for ~{3-4%minutes}, until softened. Add the @ground beef{20%ounce} and @dried oregano{2%teaspoon} to the pan and cook, breaking up the meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Rub one side of each @whole wheat tortillas{4} with a small drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} and place oil-side down on a #baking sheet{}. Sprinkle half of each tortilla with some @mozzarella cheese{1%cup}. Top with the ground beef and another sprinkling of mozzarella cheese. Fold over the other side of the tortilla and repeat for the remaining quesadillas. Bake for ~{7-10%minutes}, flipping halfway through cooking, until melted and crispy.

Cut the quesadillas into wedges and serve with a dollop of @sour cream{4%tablespoon} and a side of avocado-black bean salsa.